<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 4:18<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I266c3570630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>4.</label.designator><headtext>Constitutional Privileges</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f7ad1682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>4:18.</label.designator><headtext>Unreasonable search and seizure—Electronic surveillance, wire tapping</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Wire tapping, eavesdropping, and electronic surveillance of a person fall within the purview of the Fourth Amendment&apos;s privilege against unreasonable search and seizure. <eos/><bos/>However, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“when appropriate procedural safeguards are met, a narrowly written statute providing for a system of electronic surveillance does not constitute an unreasonable search and seizure”<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/> under either the federal or state constitutions.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic31568b07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In Georgia, all forms of electronic surveillance must follow both federal law[<footnote.reference refid="Ic31568b17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] and Georgia&apos;s wiretapping, eavesdropping, and surveillance statutes, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-11-60" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I009080e07fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. §§ 16-11-60</cite.query> to <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-11-70" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I009080e17fc011ea988285db8533e975">16-11-70</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>A superior court judge in the circuit where the listening post is located must issue a wiretap order.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic31568b27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>] Any photographic, audio, video, or other similar evidence gathered in violation of these is subject to the exclusionary rule and inadmissible at trial.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3158fc07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] The recording must be presented for sealing immediately after the surveillance ends or the authorization expires.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3158fc17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The prohibition applies to interceptions by family members too.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3158fc27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1985102362" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0092f1e27fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Ransom v. Ransom</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3158fc37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>] a husband tape-recorded his wife&apos;s telephone conversations with a third party without her knowledge or consent. <eos/><bos/>The wife subsequently filed suit for divorce and then filed a motion in limine to prevent the admission of the tapes at trial of the divorce action. <eos/><bos/>The trial court prohibited <page no="136"/>their use for any purpose except impeachment. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Supreme Court refused to recognize any exception to the statute for domestic situations and held that the taping violated <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-11-62" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I009403507fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-11-62</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>Thus, the Georgia wiretapping statutes prohibit the use of tape recordings, even for impeachment purposes.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3158fc47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1993052427" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0094c6a27fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Salmon v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic315b6d07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals construed the term “private communication” in <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-11-62" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I0095b1007fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-11-62</cite.query> to exclude conversations on a cellular telephone reasoning that <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“cellular telephones transmit ‘FM’ radio waves for anyone to hear.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0003"/> Subsequently, in an attempt to extend previous telephone land-line law to cover cellular wireless communications, the Georgia General Assembly passed legislation that specifically prohibited any person from intercepting or receiving cellular telephone communications. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2000063853" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0095b1037fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Barlow v. Barlow</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic315b6d17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court relied upon <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1993052427" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I009674527fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Salmon</ital></cite.query> to clarify that Georgia&apos;s wiretap statutes also apply to cordless telephone conversations.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2036705802" w-seq-number="00026" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0096e9827fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>London v. State,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic315b6d27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Court of Appeals reversed the admission of a telephone call between the defendant and a minor where the phone call was initiated by the minor, but at the suggestion of law enforcement, and where the minor was not aware the telephone call was being recorded.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2026902885" w-seq-number="00028" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I0097d3e17fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>United States v. Jones,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic315dde07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">12</footnote.reference>] the U.S. Supreme Court held that the government&apos;s installation of a GPS tracking device to an individual&apos;s vehicle, and the subsequent use of that device to monitor the vehicle&apos;s movements on a public street, constitute a search within the meaning of the Fourth Amendment. <eos/><bos/>Thus, the state must present probable cause to a magistrate to obtain a warrant in such a case. <eos/><bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2032550389" w-seq-number="00030" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I009933717fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Hamlett v. State,</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic315dde17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">13</footnote.reference>] the court held that there was no evidence that a defendant had been involved in a prior burglary which gave rise to the magistrate&apos;s finding of probable cause to allow the state to install and monitor a GPS tracking devise. <eos/><bos/>The court thus held that <begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>“simply producing a warrant and the supporting affidavit does <ital>not</ital> meet the state&apos;s threshold burden; it must <ital>also</ital> show <ital>through those documents or other evidence</ital> that the warrant [is valid].”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0004"/>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic315dde27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">14<page no="137"/><page no="138"/></footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic31568b07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Goger, Daniel&apos;s Georgia Criminal Trial Practice § 4:59 (2018–2019 ed.).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1966131622" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I008fbd927fc011ea988285db8533e975">Osborn v. U.S., 385 U.S. 323, 87 S. Ct. 429, 17 L. Ed. 2d 394 (1966)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1967129546" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I008fbd967fc011ea988285db8533e975">Berger v. State of N.Y., 388 U.S. 41, 87 S. Ct. 1873, 18 L. Ed. 2d 1040 (1967)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1967129584" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I008fbd9a7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Katz v. U.S., 389 U.S. 347, 88 S. Ct. 507, 19 L. Ed. 2d 576 (1967)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic31568b17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="18USCAS2510" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I009032c07fc011ea988285db8533e975">18 U.S.C.A. §§ 2510</cite.query> to <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="18USCAS2520" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I009032c17fc011ea988285db8533e975">2520</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic31568b27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2029569928" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0090cf027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Luangkhot v. State, 292 Ga. 423, 736 S.E.2d 397 (2013)</cite.query>. 2013 Ga. HB 55 amended <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-11-64" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I0090cf037fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. §§ 16-11-64</cite.query> and <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-11-66" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I0090cf047fc011ea988285db8533e975">16-11-66</cite.query> to give a wiretap order statewide application allowing electronic interception from any location in the state.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3158fc07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-11-67" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I0091b9607fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-11-67</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1992052125" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0091b9637fc011ea988285db8533e975">Dobbins v. State, 262 Ga. 161, 415 S.E.2d 168 (1992)</cite.query> (<begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“<cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST16-11-67" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I0091b9647fc011ea988285db8533e975">O.C.G.A. § 16-11-67</cite.query> provides that evidence obtained in a manner which violates any of the provisions of Title 16, Chapter 11, Article 3, Part 1, entitled Wiretapping, Eavesdropping, Surveillance, and Related Offenses, is not admissible in evidence.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>).<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3158fc17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2038422870" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I009207827fc011ea988285db8533e975">Finney v. State, 298 Ga. 620, 783 S.E.2d 598 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3158fc27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1999275092" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I00927cb27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Bishop v. State, 241 Ga. App. 517, 526 S.E.2d 917 (1999)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3158fc37fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1985102362" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I009340027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ransom v. Ransom, 253 Ga. 656, 324 S.E.2d 437 (1985)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="136"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3158fc47fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1985102362" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I00942a627fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ransom v. Ransom, 253 Ga. 656, 324 S.E.2d 437 (1985)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic315b6d07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="1993052427" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0094edb27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Salmon v. State, 206 Ga. App. 469, 470–471, 426 S.E.2d 160 (1992)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic315b6d17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2000063853" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0095d8127fc011ea988285db8533e975">Barlow v. Barlow, 272 Ga. 102, 526 S.E.2d 857 (2000)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic315b6d27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2036705802" w-seq-number="00027" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I009710927fc011ea988285db8533e975">London v. State, 333 Ga. App. 332, 775 S.E.2d 787 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic315dde07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>12</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2026902885" w-seq-number="00029" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I0097faf17fc011ea988285db8533e975">U.S. v. Jones, 132 S. Ct. 945, 181 L. Ed. 2d 911 (2012)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic315dde17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>13</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2032550389" w-seq-number="00031" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I00995a817fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hamlett v. State, 753 S.E.2d 118 (2013)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic315dde27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>14<page no="137"/><page no="138"/></label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2032550389" w-seq-number="00032" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" w-pinpoint-page="127" ID="I0099cfb17fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hamlett v. State, 753 S.E.2d 118, 127 (2013)</cite.query> (emphasis supplied by court), citing <cite.query w-src-number="0287018131" w-serial-number="2030240045" w-seq-number="00033" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I0099cfb47fc011ea988285db8533e975">Jones v. State, 292 Ga. 656, 740 S.E.2d 590 (2013)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="137"/><page no="138"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 4:18<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
